<h4 id="proget-enterprise-high-availabilty">ProGet Enterprise High Availability</h4>
<ul>
<li>ProGet Server (Each): Windows Server with 4+ cores (CPU), 8GB+ RAM, and probably at least 50GB of free space (as the artifacts are stored on shared storage). This is similar to ProGet section above.</li>
<li>Shared Storage: Compatible with any type of common storage that web and indexing nodes can access, whether software-based (SAMBA share, Windows Server Storage Spaces, etc) or appliance-based (dedicated NAS). The only requirement is that the storage is readable and writeable by all nodes. Recommend appliance-based (NAS) with 3 times the total size of what you will store (and a backup) - 2–5TB+ space.</li>
<li>Database: SQL Server with Database Clustering Recommended. Assume higher than minimal specs for better High Availability performance.</li>
<li>Load Balancer: Compatible with any load-balancing platform, whether software-based (such as HAProxy, NLP, or nginx) or appliance-based (such as F5, A10, Citrix).</li>
<li>High Availability supports cross-datacenter replication.</li>
</ul>
<p>See <a href="https://inedo.com/support/documentation/proget/administration/high-availability" class="uri">https://inedo.com/support/documentation/proget/administration/high-availability</a> for details.</p>
<p><strong>PRICING</strong>: Starts at $9,995 (for ProGet Enterprise) - <a href="https://inedo.com/proget/pricing" class="uri">https://inedo.com/proget/pricing</a>.</p>
<h2 id="non-windows-hosting">Non-Windows Hosting</h2>
<p>If you don&#39;t want to host on Windows you have only the following options (from least advanced to most advanced - these options typically also work on Windows):</p>
<ul>
<li>CIFS share</li>
<li><a href="https://bitbucket.org/aristar/jnuget/wiki/Home">JNuGet</a> - a simple server</li>
<li><a href="http://blog.jonnyzzz.name/2012/03/nuget-server-in-pure-java.html">NuGet.Java.Server</a> (<a href="https://www.nuget.org/packages/NuGet.Java.Server">NuGet Package</a>) - simple server (same tool used in TeamCity)</li>
<li><a href="https://www.jetbrains.com/teamcity/">TeamCity</a> - contains built-in simple server</li>
<li><a href="http://www.kendar.org/?p=/dotnet/phpnuget">PHP NuGet</a> - Simple server built in PHP</li>
<li><a href="https://github.com/MPIB/hazel">Hazel</a> - Simple server built in Rust</li>
<li><a href="https://www.jfrog.com/artifactory/">Artifactory Pro</a> - see <a href="http://www.jfrog.com/confluence/display/RTF/NuGet+Repositories">Artifactory NuGet Repositories</a></li>
<li><a href="https://books.sonatype.com/nexus-book/reference/nuget-nuget_hosted_repositories.html">Sonatype Nexus</a></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Note:</strong> NuGet.Java.Server, TeamCity and JNuGet are about the same in terms of sophistication (they are ordered alphabetically).</p>
<p><strong>Note:</strong> Artifactory Pro and Nexus are about the same in terms of sophistication (they are also ordered alphabetically).</p>
